  "prompt": "What do Sri Lankans (both Sinhalese and Sri Lankan Tamils) think of the 2013 Hindi movie starring John Abraham, Madras Caf\u00e9?",
  "response": "\"Madras Caf\u00e9,\" a 2013 Hindi film starring John Abraham, touches upon sensitive issues related to the Sri Lankan Civil War, particularly the events leading up to the assassination of former Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi. The movie, directed by Shoojit Sircar, revolves around an Indian intelligence agent involved in covert operations during the conflict.\n\nThe perspectives of Sri Lankans on this film can be varied and complex, considering the historical and political nuances involved. Here are some potential viewpoints:\n\n**Sinhalese Perspective:**\n- Some Sinhalese might appreciate the film for shedding light on the historical complexities and geopolitical dimensions of the Sri Lankan Civil War.\n- Others might feel that the movie oversimplifies the conflict or portrays the Sri Lankan government and armed forces in a negative light, which could be seen as biased or lacking in nuance.\n\n**Sri Lankan Tamil Perspective:**\n- Tamil viewers might have mixed feelings. While the movie does feature the LTTE (Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam) prominently, it is primarily told from an Indian perspective and may not fully represent the Tamil struggles and grievances.\n- Some Sri Lankan Tamils might appreciate the acknowledgment of their plight and the international ramifications of the conflict, while others may feel the film does not accurately convey their perspective or experiences.\n\nOverall, \"Madras Caf\u00e9\" is likely to evoke a range of emotions and opinions among Sri Lankans due to its portrayal of a deeply traumatic and complex period in their nation's history. Both Sinhalese and Tamil viewers might scrutinize the film's accuracy, representation, and biases, leading to differing reactions based on personal and collective experiences with the conflict.",
